Taiwan Stocks: Motech Industries, HTC, Kinsus, Nan Ya Printed

-- B y   W e i y i   L i m
-- 
2011-03-16T06:08:41Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-16/au-optronics-chimei-innolux-hon-hai-taiwan-stocks-preview.html
Stocks of the following companies
had unusual moves in Taiwan trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 1:30 p.m. close.  The Taiex Index rose 89.80, or 1.1 percent, to 8,324.58.  Solar Energy-related companies:  Motech Industries Inc. (6244) 
(6244 TT) surged 6.9 percent to NT$131 and  Sino-American Silicon
Products Inc. (5483)  (5483 TT) jumped 6.9 percent to NT$131.50. The
solar-panel component makers rose on speculation renewable
energy will benefit in the aftermath of Japan’s nuclear-reactor
accident, said Jennifer Liang, an analyst at KGI Securities Co.    AU Optronics Corp. (2409)  (2409 TT) gained 1 percent to NT$24.60.
Taiwan’s second-largest flat panel maker has experienced no
short-term supply constraints after the March 11 earthquake in
Japan, with some materials makers there already resuming
production, executive vice president Paul Peng said yesterday in
Taipei.    Chimei Innolux Corp. (3481)  (3481 TT) increased 1.4 percent to
NT$29.85. Taiwan’s largest flat panel maker plans to ship 3
million 3D panels for a market share of about 35 percent in  China  this year, the Miaoli, Taiwan-based company said in a
statement on its website yesterday.    Kinsus Interconnect Technology Corp. (3189)  (3189 TT) dropped 3.9
percent to NT$80.40, the lowest since Oct. 19.  Unimicron
Technology Corp. (3037)  (3037 TT) retreated 1.8 percent to NT$47.15.  Nan Ya Printed Circuit Board Corp. (8046)  (8046 TT) lost 4 percent to
NT$90.20. The companies will “suffer” the most from shortages
of BT resin, used in electronic devices, due to the Japanese
temblor, according to a report by Credit Suisse Group AG.    HTC Corp. (2498)  (2498 TT) climbed 6.7 percent to NT$1,030, the
most since Feb. 25, after Chief Executive Officer Peter Chou
said there is no shortage of materials and the company is in
close contact with its Japanese suppliers after  Japan ’s worst
earthquake.  To contact the reporter on this story:
